  "doc_id": "14673",
  "text": "Studies have shown that in adult bone marrow and circulating blood there is a population of cells similar to embryonic angioblasts, known as endothelial progenitor cells (EPCs). These cells are types of stem/progenitor cells with the potential to differentiate into mature endothelial cells and to settle among injured vascular endothelial cells in order to repair damaged blood vessels. In humans, EPCs have been characterized as CD133, CD34, and VEGFR2 (KDR) positive cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
